25 Martin Place by @jamesnielsen_design 
⁠
"Sydney’s ‘White Beacon’⁠
⁠
An icon of the Sydney skyline, 25 Martin Place (previously the MLC Centre) has been an Australian living landmark for over 40 years. The new name, 25 Martin Place, celebrates the location in the heart of the world’s greatest harbour city. When visionary architect Harry Seidler gifted Sydney the building in 1978, it was unlike anything Australia had seen before. ⁠
⁠
The building was inspired by classic Bauhaus foundations, where form follows function and celebrated a deep love of geometry intersecting with modern purpose. Honoring this the identity builds on Seidler’s design principles and plays on the existing geometric form that is the White Beacon. True to the Bauhaus movement it is refined, simple and clean, doing away with unnecessary embellishment. ⁠
⁠
Today, 25 Martin Place is the centrepiece of Sydney, where visitors embrace fashion, dining, business, and culture. From new luxury and premium brands on Castlereagh and King Streets to a collection of refined restaurants and bars bringing the outdoor plaza to life. ⁠
⁠
Agency: The Hallway⁠
Photography (Food): Joh Bader⁠
Photography (Fashion): Steven Popovich"

Ziu I.A by @an___ker⁠
⁠
"Ziu I.A is a Hong Kong based-interior design and floral arrangement studio. The amalgamation of the two stems from their core purpose: to orchestrate unique narratives that heighten the sensory experience of spaces.⁠
⁠
The colour palette that we chose for this project is inspired by nature. The green and beige tones recreate the mood that we often identify with ‘Mornings’. When the morning comes, rays of sunlight slowly shines into our homes, awakening us from our vague. Vague, yet full of vitality and hope. The direction taken echoes the founder's vision for the studio."

A CUP OF COFFEE by Kai Ting Yong⁠
⁠
"A Cup of Coffee is a brand concept that utilizes basic mathematical operations as a form of design aesthetics within a brand identity. This project aims to provide a new perspective by using equations, formulas and bar graphs to visualize information and create a visual language. It attempts to influence how consumers comprehend information and provide an alternative visual method to learn more about coffee as they enjoy it."
